<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / BA scraps 500 supervisor posts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AIRWAYS has abolished more than 500 supervisor posts as part of a
flexible-working deal agreed with unions representing almost 4,000
engineering and maintenance staff at Heathrow, Gatwick and Glasgow.
Mr Alistair Cummings, BA's director of engineering, said: 'We realised
supervisors were doing an impossible job. They had to combine aspects of man
management, the organisation of production, problem-solving and material
shortages.'
Former supervisors will be absorbed into teams responsible for one or other
of those functions. Some will be promoted into the upper layers of
production control management within a new production control unit on the
shop floor.
The move is consistent with recent research by the Confederation of British
Industry and the National Economic Development Council. Both criticised the
competence and development of Britain's supervisors, who number more than
1m.
BA's approach to the matter fits in with recommendations that the job of
supervisor should be rethought. Some functions should be transferred to
management and others to production team leaders.
The airline says the wider deal, agreed with the AEEU electrical and
engineering union and the MSF professional and technical union, underlines
the sea change in relations with engineering staff. It believes the deal
means immediate productivity gains of 5 per cent to 10 per cent.
In the longer term, BA hopes the new arrangement will allow it to undertake
more work for other airlines because of the end of demarcation among
engineering staff and the creation of a multi-skilled workforce through
training.
It introduces a simplified pay structure that consolidates allowances into
basic pay. That means improved sick pay and pension benefits. The airline
says all jobs are secure and the deal will improve long-term prospects for
staff.
During the 1980s and early 1990, BA and its engineering staff were involved
in a number of disputes over pay and flexibility. BA says relations were
hampered by a lack of trust on both sides. The airline believes the vital
groundwork for the new agreement was laid in 1986 when the two sides agreed
a measure of flexibility. Union fears of job losses proved groundless.
Management and unions cemented their working relationship in 1990 when the
two sides met frequently to discuss changes in the airline.
Mr Roger Butler, an AEEU executive council member, welcomed the deal, which
he said would protect jobs: 'This multi-skilled training package gives the
workers higher skills and more independence. It also gives them a lot more
trust and responsibility.'
He said the abolition of the supervisors was sensible, since it had been
proved that the workforce could self-supervise.
</TEXT>
