<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / Veil of Whitehall secrecy is lifted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAREER DETAILS of the head of MI5 are given in the first edition of a new
guide to Whitehall, published with official blessing - but no reference is
made to the head of foreign intelligence.
Dod's Whitehall Companion, produced with the encouragement of Sir Robin
Butler, the head of the Civil Service, provides information on 980 top civil
servants, ministerial advisers, regulators and executive agency chiefs.
It contains a brief biographical note on Mrs Stella Rimington, head of the
MI5, but there is no entry for Sir Colin McColl, her counterpart at MI6.
Dod's gives details of present jobs, past careers, education and recreations
of mandarins as well as addresses and telephone numbers.
Many of those listed have also supplied photographs of themselves.
Apart from the reference to Mrs Rimington, information is given about the
Security Commission - which deals with Whitehall leaks - and the Security
Service Tribunal, which investigates complaints against the security
service.
The guide also discloses previously unpublished information about the
responsibilities of individual civil servants, including those working in
the Cabinet Office and at for the prime minister at No 10 Downing Street.
Detailed organisation charts for each government department show the links
between individual ministers, top civil servants and departmental divisions.
Sir Robin Butler played a central role in producing the guide, arranging
access for the compilers.
In his foreword to the book, Sir Robin welcomes its publication as
'consistent with the mood of open govern-ment'.
The Whitehall Companion 1992. Dod's Publishing and Research. Pounds 125.
</TEXT>
