FT  23 SEP 92 / The ERM and Maastricht: Britain pushessingle market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN, which currently holds the EC presidency, yesterday called for
member states to rally round the single market project as an antidote to
turmoil elsewhere in the Community.
Mr Richard Needham, UK trade minister, told internal market ministers they
should make a special effort to complete the barrier-free market by the
January 1, 1993 deadline.
But within hours of the start of yesterday's meeting, the 12 ministers were
embroiled in a familiar but fruitless debate about the working language of
the planned European trademark office. The office is supposed to provide a
single agency for EC companies to register trademarks.
Ministers agreed yesterday that EC leaders should discuss a second problem -
the site of the office - at the Edinburgh summit. Similar problems with the
location of various new European agencies will also be raised there.
But the 12 were unable to settle the dispute about whether the office should
accept trademark applications in any of the nine official EC languages or
adopt a simpler and cheaper system based on the use of English, French and
German.
The Commission has estimated that a nine-tongue solution could cost as much
as Ecu112m (Pounds 87m) to initiate.
Yesterday's meeting was also addressed by Mr Peter Sutherland, a former EC
competition commissioner, who is working on a report on how to implement and
enforce the market. He said before the meeting that member states should not
be allowed to invoke the concept of subsidiarity to wriggle out of single
market commitments.
The committee he is chairing is likely to recommend centralised controls to
help settle disputes which cannot be solved at national level.
'Subsidiarityshould not be used to wriggle out of single market commitments'
</TEXT>
