<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / Yugoslav plea to avert exclusion from UN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS and JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Milan Panic, prime minister of the rump state of Yugoslavia, warned the
United Nations last night that exclusion of his country's delegation from UN
activities would set a bad precedent.
In a last minute bid to avert his delegation's exclusion from the UN general
assembly, Mr Panic argued that his state - consisting only of Serbia and
Montenegro - fulfilled all requirements of UN membership.
Sir David Hannay, Britain's ambassador, formally introduced a resolution to
exclude the rump state, following the declarations of independence by other
republics in the former Yugoslavia.
Sir David said the exclusion was in no sense a 'punitive measure' against
Serbia nor one designed to undermine the Yugoslav peace process.
He said it was only designed to deny the Serb-controlled rump state's right
to inherit the UN seat Yugoslavia held before its break-up.
Mr Panic served notice that he would formally apply for the new federation's
readmission.
Earlier, he pleaded his case in an hour-long meeting with the foreign
ministers of the council's five permanent members - the US, Britain, France,
Russia and China - who reaffirmed their rejection of Belgrade's claim to be
the automatic successor to a state that was a founding member of the UN.
Mr Douglas Hurd, British foreign secretary, repeated that position on behalf
of the European Community in his address to the Assembly yesterday and
insisted that a delegation from the new 'Federal Republic of Yugoslavia'
should not participate in the work of the General Assembly.
Privately, western officials stressed that they did not want to do anything
to harm Mr Panic's standing and they acknowledged his political courage. But
they reiterated their view that Serbia and Montenegro must follow the same
route as the other republics of former Yugoslavia and apply for independent
membership if it wished to be in the UN.
Mr Lawrence Eagleburger, the US acting secretary of state, told reporters he
believed Mr Panic was working hard and constructively to bring peace to the
region, but both he and Mr Hurd agreed there were 'very serious problems' to
be resolved before the penalties imposed on Belgrade could be lifted. Any of
the permanent members of the Security Council could block its membership
application through a veto.
In an appeal addressed to all UN members, Mr Panic said the case of
Belgrade's membership affected the rights of all small states and its
expulsion would set a dangerous precedent. 'Today it is Yugoslavia; tomorrow
it may as well be any other member state of the United Nations,' he said.
Mr Panic is determined to strengthen his fragile base in Serbia, despite
attempts by Serbia's ruling socialist party to threaten another
no-confidence vote against him.
As soon as he returns to Belgrade, he will try to gain control over
television, currently monopolised by Serbian president Slobodan Milosevic.
Television is the main source of information for the countryside which
continues to support Mr Milosevic.
To achieve this, Mr Panic wants to change the federal constitution, in a
move aimed at placing the television, or at least one of the two main
channels, under federal control.
</TEXT>
