<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / Gaidar promises to fight hyperinflation: Prices rose 15-fold
in last 12 months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD and DMITRI VOLKOV
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Yegor Gaidar, Russia's acting prime minister, yesterday told a sullen
Russian parliament that the government would seek to enforce a tough credit
and monetary policy in an effort to stem the spiralling budget deficit and
hyperinflation.
In his starkest speech since taking command of economic reform less than a
year ago, the 36-year-old Mr Gaidar said the recent relaxation of tough
monetary policy had reached a dangerous point, and must be reversed. 'We
will have to toughen monetary policy in order to stop a destabilisation of
the monetary system,' he said.
In the short debate following his speech, deputies called for his
resignation. Significantly, these calls came from leading members of
centrist groups which had reluctantly supported the government in the past.
Mr Gaidar said later he had no intention of resigning.
Mr Sergei Polozhkov from the centrist Smena faction said that Russian
industry would soon stop completely, and called for an 'anti-crisis
programme' and for the resignation of Mr Andrei Nechaev, the economics
minister, Mr Anatoly Chubais, the deputy prime minister in charge of
privatisation and Mr Peter Aven, the minister for foreign economic
relations. Mr Mikhail Chelnokov of the Civil Society faction said that the
reform 'was carried out in the interests of foreign business', and called on
Mr Gaidar to resign.
Mr Gaidar and his colleagues have dispensed with any efforts to put a
positive gloss on the reform process, emphasising instead the catastrophic
nature of the country's finances and productive base in the apparent hope
that this will jolt the country into accepting a renewed squeeze on
expenditure. However, as Mr Gaidar has recently noted, they face an
organised and aroused opposition and a weary population.
In his speech, Mr Gaidar painted a picture of a country racing towards
collapse. Production last month was down 27 per cent on the previous August,
capital investment had been cut by 46 per cent this year, and would be down
by around 55 per cent on the whole year; the budget deficit stood at the end
of the first eight months at Rbs800bn; inflation was rising to 4 per cent a
week, or more than 20 per cent a month; prices had increased 15.6 times in
the year to last month, while wages had gone up 10.6 times; 13m people lived
below a (very low) poverty line of Rbs1,200 income a month (Dollars 5 at
yesterday's new market rate for the rouble).
The prime minister pointed out that living standards were at the level of
the early seventies, before the Soviet Union enjoyed the benefits of the oil
price rises. He forecast a harvest of 96.7m tonnes of grain - significantly
below the 110m tonnes forecast less than two weeks ago by Mr Boris Yeltsin,
the Russian president, although better than last year's. However, livestock
production had declined by 23 per cent, as producers stopped breeding
because they could not afford fodder.
The only good news was the privatisation of 18,000 small businesses and
shops with receipts to the government of Rbs10bn - though this was far
behind the annual target of Rbs96bn. Unemployment stands at only 500,000 in
Russia, but is expected to grow to 1.5m by the year end - still only 2 per
cent of the workforce, but also a sign that industrial restructuring has not
yet taken hold.
</TEXT>
