<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / EC tries to resolve Macedonia name clash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A FRESH European Community effort is under way to find a name under which
the former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia can be given international
recognition without offending Greece.
Mr Robin O'Neill, a British diplomat, is holding talks today in Skopje, the
Macedonian capital, after meeting Greek officials in Athens last week.
Mr Kiro Gligorev, the Macedonian president, has so far ruled out a name
change after the refusal of the EC, under pressure from Greece, to recognise
the republic under the name of Macedonia.
Nevertheless, other EC members remain sceptical of the Greek argument that
Macedonia's choice of an ancient Greek name amounts to a territorial claim
on the modern Greek province of Macedonia.
Mr Gligorev will probably be asked to compromise on a double name: Macedonia
would be recognised abroad under a different name, while at home it could
still call itself Macedonia.
</TEXT>
