<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / Home loan rates set to fall: Lamont looks to regain economic
initiative with one-point rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK government yesterday took full advantage of the freedom conferred by
a floating pound to cut interest rates by 1 percentage point, bringing them
below short-term rates in Germany for the first time for more than 11 years.
The effort by Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, to regain the initiative
over UK economic policy was swiftly followed by announcements from banks and
building societies that they would cut mortgage rates by around  3/4 of a
percentage point.
The move came less than a week after 'Black Wednesday' when the government
had to suspend sterling from the European exchange rate mechanism, thereby
abandoning the central plank of its economic policy .
The decision to take rates to their lowest levels since mid-1988, was taken
after consultations yesterday morning between the chancellor and Mr John
Major, the prime minister. It is designed to raise the spirits of
Conservative backbenchers ahead of tomorrow's emergency Commons debate on
the economy.
The move will also reinforce the impression at Westminster that Mr Major's
priority now is to rebuild his support among Tory MPs, even at the expense
of some higher inflation.
The chancellor made it clear yesterday that he 'was not going to take any
risks with inflation' and would raise rates again should price rises
accelerate.
The cut in commercial banks' base rates from 10 per cent to 9 per cent came
shortly after the Bank of England reduced the rates at which it lends to the
banking system just before 10am.
The pound shrugged off the cut in interest rates, which had been widely
expected in the City, although a bigger-than-expected rise in the German
money supply dampened prospects of another early rate cut.
Some industrialists and politicians warned yesterday that further reductions
in borrowing costs were necessary to lift Britain from its longest recession
for 50 years.
Sterling closed in London up  3/4 of a pfennig on the day against the D-Mark
at DM2.5450, but in late New York trading it was quoted at DM2.539. It was
barely changed against the dollar in London at Dollars 1.7090, although it
finished in New York at Dollars 1.695.
The Leeds Permanent building society, with half a million borrowers, was the
first of the big mortgage lenders to cut its basic rate by 0.75 per cent
from 10.7 per cent to 9.95 per cent.
The Abbey National followed with a pledge to cut mortgage rates by 'around
0.75 per cent', but the Halifax said it would wait to see how the markets
settled before deciding by how much to reduce its lending rates. A reduction
of 0.75 of a percentage point would take the average cost of a Pounds 30,000
mortgage down by just over Pounds 11 a month.
Mr Lamont said the cut was justified on both fundamental economic grounds
and recent sharp falls in inflation but he stressed he was determined to
press on with the government's policy to reduce inflation.
Yesterday's move is expected to lift some of the gloom stifling economic
activity, but worse-than-expected trade figures came as a reminder of the
difficulties facing the UK economy.
Figures from the Central Statistical Office showed that the UK's deficit on
visible goods, excluding oil and erratic items, was Pounds 1.7bn, its
highest level for two years. It followed an underlying rise in import
volumes to record levels and a levelling off in exports growth. The devalued
pound could make imports more expensive, but will make exports more
competitive.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, said: 'While this interest rate
reduction must of course be welcomed, it is essential that it is accompanied
by immediate action to improve the long-term performance of the economy.'
