<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / Pressure intensifies for further realignment of ERM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ, ANDREW FISHER and PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, FRANKFURT, MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE FOR a further realignment of the European exchange rate mechanism
intensified last night after five of the system's remaining currencies
dropped close to their ERM floors against the D-Mark.
Four European central banks intervened heavily on the foreign exchange
markets yesterday, buying their currencies for the D-Mark after an
unexpectedly strong figure for Germany's monetary growth in August indicated
that the Bundesbank would be unable to cut interest rates further.
A spokesman for the French finance ministry denied rumours that the ERM
would be suspended altogether and that the French franc would be devalued
against the D-Mark. Mr Hans Tietmeyer, the Bundesbank vice-president, said
in Washington that he did not see a D-Mark revaluation happening.
Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister, who was in Washington for the
World Bank/International Monetary Fund meetings, said last night he saw no
need for 'further adjustment' after last week's turmoil on the currency
markets. Speaking to journalists he also said there was no good reason for
speculators to attack the French franc.
Mr Waigel's comments came after he had abruptly cancelled his scheduled
appointments and attended what German embassy officials there described only
as a 'series of bilateral meetings'.
It was not immediately clear with which countries he had conferred. But
after a day in which a number of currencies were pushed close to their floor
levels in the European exchange rate mechanism, the move raised speculation
that a further ERM upheaval could be imminent.
Further fuelling this suspicion were reports that several EC financial
policymakers - including Mr Michel Sapin, the French finance minister, and
Mr Horst Kohler, Mr Waigel's top official - were flying back early from
Washington. Community and national officials maintained their denial of
rumours earlier in the day that a meeting of the European Community Monetary
from Committee, which is composed of representatives of finance ministries
and central banks, was about to be convened.
Mr Waigel later reaffirmed Germany's commitment to the European Monetary
System and said it would do 'everything possible' to allow currencies that
have temporarily left the exchange rate mechanism of the EMS to return to
it.
On the foreign exchange markets, the falls in the value of the French franc,
the Spanish peseta, the Portuguese escudo, the Dan-ish krone and the Irish
punt came within a week of the sus-pension of sterling and the Italian lira
from the ERM.
The Bank of France intervened for the fourth trading day running, buying
francs for D-Marks, as its currency threatened to fall to its ERM floor
against the D-Mark of FFr3.4305. Dealers said that the French central bank's
intervention was substantial, but the franc closed in London at FFr3.4260.
The Spanish peseta and the Portuguese escudo also came under intense selling
pressure. The Bank of Spain intervened to defend the peseta for the first
time since its currency was devalued by 5 per cent last week. But the peseta
closed at Pta71.91 to the D-Mark, very near to its new ERM floor of
Pta72.62. The Portuguese escudo slipped below Esc89 to the D-Mark, close to
its floor of 92.33.
The Dutch central bank bought the Irish punt and the Danish krone for the
Dutch guilder, which was yesterday the second strongest ERM currency.
In Frankfurt the Bundesbank said that M3, the broad monetary aggregate, had
expanded at an annualised rate of 9 per cent from 8.5 per cent in July. This
suggests inflationary pressures in Germany are still high and that German
interest rates may not be reduced again for some time.
The figure for August M3 money supply compares with the Bundesbank's target
range of between 3.5 and 5.5 per cent for the full year.
Money supply spectre, Page 2
Germany cast shadow over fall in rates, Page 9
Editorial Comment; Bundesbank is hard act to follow, Page 18
</TEXT>
