<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / Increase in people living alone
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SINGLE people living on their own account for more than a quarter of
households in Britain, according to official figures released today, John
Willman writes.
The 1991 General Household Survey also shows that almost two thirds of women
with dependent children are in work or seeking work and 70 per cent of
parents with children under five use some form of childcare.
The figures are among preliminary results published today by the Office of
Population Censuses and Surveys. The survey, the most authoritative guide to
households in Great Britain, is based on interviews with 19,229 adults in
9,955 households.
The size of the average household in Great Britain has decreased from 2.91
in 1971 to 2.48 last year. That has been caused largely by more
single-person households, up from 17 per cent in 1971 to 26 per cent last
year.
General Household Survey: preliminary results for 1991. OPCS Monitor SS
92/1. Pounds 2.50.
</TEXT>
