<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / Atom technology body makes profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AEA Technology
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
formerly the UK Atomic Energy Authority - made a net profit of Pounds 16.8m
in the year to 31 March 1992, its first surplus since 1987.
Last year AEA reported a Pounds 40m net loss.
The 1991-92 results, announced yesterday, show that state-owned AEA is
expanding its sales of non-nuclear industrial technology rapidly to make up
for the decline in government-funded nuclear research.
Total turnover has been steady for the past five years at about Pounds 440m
a year, while the industrial division's sales rose from Pounds 85m in
1990-91 to Pounds 105m in 1991-92 and a projected Pounds 130m in 1992-93.
AEA is a candidate for privatisation in the mid 1990s - although there has
been speculation that the government may want to break it up first into
separate nuclear and non-nuclear businesses.
Mr Brian Eyre, chief executive, said in an interview that he welcomed
privatisation 'though not at the expense of breaking up the organisation'.
He said: 'If it was broken up, we would lose many of our strengths, and I
would be fundamentally opposed to that.'
Mr Eyre said there were many examples of AEA's nuclear and non-nuclear
divisions working together - for instance, similar technology was used to
clean up chemical and radioactive wastes.
AEA is also expanding overseas, with international sales up 16 per cent to
Pounds 44m in 1991-92.
It has made its first overseas acquisition: O'Donnell, a specialist US
engineering consultancy bought for Pounds 2.2m. It will use AEA O'Donnell,
as it is now called, as a route into the American market.
Meanwhile the UK workforce continues to contract. The number of people
employed fell by 1,000 during the year to 9,750.
</TEXT>
