FT  23 SEP 92 / The ERM and Maastricht: Waigel tries to soothe markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Theo Waigel, Germany's finance minister, said last night he saw no need
for 'further adjustment' after last week's turmoil on the currency markets.
His attempt to calm the markets was made in a speech at the IMF annual
meeting in Washington after a day of rumours of a further impending
realignment in the European Exchange Rate Mechanism.
Mr Waigel referred to the suspension of sterling and the Italian lira from
the ERM and the French Yes vote on the Maastricht treaty. The French vote,
he said, had taken an important element of uncertainty from the markets.
Then he added: 'After last week's decisions, there is no further need for
adjustment, as a look at economic fundamentals shows.'
Emerging later from the IMF meeting, Mr Waigel laughed off questions about a
possible realignment of currencies in the ERM. 'I never comment about
marriages and currency movements,' he told reporters.
But he went on to say there was no good reason for speculators to attack the
franc. 'French fundamentals are in order,' he said.
In his IMF speech, Mr Waigel pledged that Germany would continue to meet
fully its obligations in the European Monetary System.
He repeated that German interest rates were not, in his view, at the root of
the currency market's upheaval. 'German capital market interest rates are,
at 7.6 per cent, the lowest in Europe, barring Switzerland; the same goes
for money market rates. The capital movements into the D-Mark obviously have
other causes,' he said.
In a day of rumours of further currency changes, finance ministry officials
visiting Washington for the IMF session scuttled surreptitiously from
meeting to meeting, anxiously skirting clusters of journalists trying to
ambush them.
Gossip of impossible precision insisted that Mr Michel Sapin, France's
finance minister, would announce a realignment at the crack of dawn today,
after flying back to Paris from Washington.
</TEXT>
