<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 92 / World Trade News: Egyptian reactor deal for Argentina
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FERGUS NICOLL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Egyptian Atomic Energy Authority has awarded a contract to build the
country's first nuclear reactor in more than 30 years to the Argentinian
company Investigaciones Aplicadas (INVAP).
Egypt's only existing nuclear plant, built by the Soviet Union in 1961 at
Inshas (55km north-east of Cairo), is to be dismantled.
INVAP won the tender for the 22-MW research plant over rival bids from
General Atomics, the US group, Atomic Energy of Canada, and a Franco-German
consortium of Siemens and Framaton.
Mr Maher Abaza, Egypt's minister of power and electricity, said the
five-year project will cost Dollars 44.47m (Pounds 25.1m), plus Dollars
16.6m for sub-contracted construction and locally-manufactured components.
Work on the first phase will begin before the end of the year.
Mr Jorge de Belaustegui, Argentina's ambassador to Egypt, joined the
Egyptians in stressing that the new reactor would carry out no military
research, and would be built and run under the auspices of the International
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).
The two countries were previously linked in a military capacity in the
aborted development of the Condor-2 missile in the late 1980s.
Egypt had ambitious plans in the early 1980s for several power-generating
plants but these were shelved after the 1986 Chernobyl disaster.
It remains to be seen whether the new research plant will lead to new
contracts for power generators.
The official media in China reported in July that Egypt was ready to order a
300-MW reactor. President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt is due to make an official
visit to China in October.
</TEXT>
