<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 92 / International Company News: BankAmerica purchase raises
presence in Texas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANKAMERICA, the leading bank in the western US, yesterday moved to
strengthen its modest presence in the important Texas market with the
purchase of 130 branches and Dollars 7.5bn of deposits from First Gibraltar
Bank, a large savings institution controlled by the financier Mr Ronald
Perelman.
The deal, part of the consolidation of the fragmented US banking industry,
came as North Carolina-based First Union agreed to buy Virginia-based
Dominion Bankshares for stock valued at Dollars 850m.
Californian-based BankAmerica said the cost of the First Gibraltar deal was
expected to be around Dollars 110m, mainly in cash, paid to MacAndrews &amp;
Forbes Holdings, the parent company behind Mr Perelman's privately-owned
empire.
Mr Perelman's acquisition of First Gibraltar four years ago created immense
controversy because of the favourable terms he won from a government agency
overseeing the national crisis of failed savings and loans institutions.
He pieced together First Gibraltar from failed thrifts acquired for Dollars
355m, while gaining Dollars 900m in tax breaks and a contract to manage
distressed loans held by the institutions. He now appears to have utilised
most of the tax breaks and management fees.
First Gibraltar was put up for sale earlier this year. But despite its
extensive branch network, its attractions for potential purchasers were
reduced by its relatively slim loan book and lack of business customers.
BankAmerica said it would be buying some Dollars 225m of commercial loans
and Dollars 640m of consumer loans. MacAndrews &amp; Forbes would retain First
Gibraltar's federal savings bank charter, four branches in Plano,Texas, and
non-banking subsidiaries.
BankAmerica operates 130 branches in Texas and has some Dollars 3.7bn of
deposits. It claimed the deal would boost it to second place in the state in
terms of branches, behind North Carolina-based NationsBank, and fourth
position in terms of deposits.
The Californian bank moved into Texas in 1991, buying the assets of a
troubled Houston bank, and followed this up with deals involving two
thrifts.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
