<PROFILE>_AN-CIVBVADSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920922
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 92 / International Company News: Nike improves but share price
varies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NIKE, the US sports shoe and apparel maker, saw its share price fluctuate
yesterday after reporting an improvement in first-quarter profits.
Nike lifted net income to Dollars 122.6m, or Dollars 1.60 a share, a 7 per
cent improvement from the Dollars 114.4m, or Dollars 1.50, reported a year
earlier.
Although earnings were strong in a difficult retail climate, they
disappointed Wall Street initially. Analysts had been looking for earnings
of about Dollars 1.70 a share and, by mid-session, its shares had slipped
Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 74 3/4 , but reversed direction to close at Dollars
76 3/8 , up Dollars  7/8 .
The company said first-quarter expenses were unusually high, reflecting
increased advertising linked to the Barcelona Olympics and the launch of new
brands. Mr Philip Knight, chairman, said: 'Management strongly believe that
these investments will add to Nike's momentum in key international markets
and allow us to achieve out stated full-year earnings growth objective of 15
per cent.'
During the quarter, revenues rose 16 per cent to Dollars 1.1bn from Dollars
947.2m. Growth was led by international sales, which soared 44 per cent to
Dollars 357.7m.
Excluding the impact of dollar translations, overseas revenues rose 32 per
cent. In contrast, domestic footwear and apparel revenues advanced only 5
per cent to Dollars 687.7m, while revenues from other brands jumped 30 per
cent to Dollars 54.4m. Orders for footwear and apparel scheduled for
delivery between September 1992 and January 1993 rose 27 per cent to Dollars
1.36bn.
Nike's consolidated gross margin improved to 39.4 per cent, against 38.7 per
cent the previous year.
</TEXT>
