<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 92 / Panic pleads his case at UN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS AT THE UN and FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Milan Panic, prime minister of the rump state of Yugoslavia, flew to New
York yesterday to plead his country's case at the United Nations.
He held urgent talks with diplomats as the UN General Assembly prepared to
consider ousting the delegation of Serbia and Montenegro, whose claim to
succeed to the Yugoslav seat has been rejected by the Security Council.
Diplomats said last night they had little doubt the 179-nation body would
endorse the decision, making it necessary for Belgrade to re-apply for
membership.
Mr Panic argued that expulsion of Yugoslavia would be 'wholly
unprecedented', adding: 'Countries at war like Iraq and Iran were never
expelled even though they committed atrocities.'
President Alija Izetbegovic of Bosnia-Hercegovina meanwhile urged the
General Assembly to lift the arms embargo imposed when his republic was
still part of Yugoslavia. Now, he said, his nation was being strangled by
the ban, deprived of means to respond to an aggressor.
Mr Izetbegovic flew to New York after attending peace talks in Geneva
sponsored by the UN and the European Community. The Geneva negotiations will
continue between lower-ranking officials.
The co-chairmen of the Geneva conference, Mr Cyrus Vance, for the UN, and
Lord Owen, representing the EC, fly to Athens today to discuss the situation
in the former Yugo-slav republic of Macedonia with Greek Prime Minister
Konstantinos Mitsotakis. Greece has blocked international recognition of
Macedonia, for fear the newly independent republic could pursue claims to
Greek territory of the same name.
Mr James Grant, executive director of the United Nations Children's Fund
(Unicef), said yesterday that all parties to the Yugoslav conflict had
agreed special measures to protect children from violence.
This would culminate in a 'children's week' in the first week of November,
by which time Unicef hoped to have distributed clothing, restarted the
immunisation programme and got children back to school. However, he admitted
that he had nothing in writing.
More than 1,000 children have died, and 30,000 have been wounded, in the
Bosnian conflict.
