<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 92 / German bank says UK must negotiate re-entry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign and Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON AND LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE German Bundesbank yesterday served notice that the UK will have to
negotiate sterling's re-entry into the European exchange rate mechanism at
an appropriate parity as the currency fell to a new low against the D-Mark.
In remarks which are likely to irritate the British government, Mr Helmut
Schlesinger, the Bundesbank president, said that the re-entry of sterling
and the lira into the ERM would have to be on terms approved by all other
participants.
The ERM remained under heavy strain yesterday after France's narrow approval
of the Maastricht treaty failed to allay investors' fears about the future
of European monetary union.
The French franc dropped to within two centimes of its ERM floor against the
D-Mark, in spite of continuous intervention by the Bank of France, and
supportive comments from Mr Schlesinger.
Ireland's punt was again the victim of heavy selling as investors continued
to buy D-Marks.
In Italy, the central bank's announcement that it would not rejoin the ERM
today, as it suggested last week, triggered another heavy sell-off of the
Italian currency against the D-Mark. It closed in London at L845.2, from a
previous close of L836.2, although it picked up in early Far East trading
today where it was quoted at about L842.2.
Sterling, which left the ERM last week, fell as speculators anticipated an
early cut in UK base rates.
The pound closed in London 7 1/2 pfennigs down from Friday's close at
DM2.5375, an historic low against the D-Mark and an effective 10 per cent
devaluation from the old ERM central rate. In New York it finished the day
at DM2.5338, and slipped a shade further to around DM2.53 as Far East
trading opened.
Sterling also fell against the dollar, finishing in New York at Dollars
1.7080, more than 2 1/2 cents down on Friday's close. Early today in the Far
East it gained slightly to about Dollars 1.7130.
Without specifically naming the pound, Mr Schlesinger said it was 'very
important' that countries entering the ERM should choose a parity that
'would be right from the beginning'. This had not happened in the past.
Mr Schlesinger's remarks reflect the continued distaste the Bundesbank has
for the way the UK entered the ERM in October 1990. At that time UK
unilaterally decided that sterling's parity would be DM2.95 and announced
the rate before the weekend meetings of EC officials which were to discuss
UK entry.
Mr Schlesinger's insistence that the UK submit its proposed entry terms to
its EC partners is in line with ERM rules.
But it is likely to irritate Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, who at the
weekend made clear the UK wanted changes in the ERM before again submitting
sterling to its disciplines.
Last night he voiced hopes that the French vote would help calm the markets.
He added that although sterling was outside the ERM, 'our policies will
continue to be directed at achieving the objective of sustained
non-inflationary growth over the medium term, and of meeting the convergence
conditions set out in the Maastricht treaty'.
The ERM had difficulty coping with the D-Mark as its anchor currency after
German union, he said, and called on the EC to address the 'rationale' of
the ERM. One issue was whether it should revert to a system of fixed but
adjustable parities, as was the case before 1987, or 'a glide path towards a
single currency'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
