FT  22 SEP 92 / Chemicals explosion leaves two people dead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON and ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FULL inquiry is to be carried out into yesterday's explosion at a
chemicals plant in Castleford, West Yorkshire, which left two people dead
and 15 injured, four seriously.
The blast occurred at 1.30pm at the manufacturing plant of Hickson and
Welch, an organic chemicals subsidiary of Hickson International, the
Yorkshire-based chemicals group.
In addition to a health and safety executive inquiry, the company is to
conduct its own investigation of the incident. The full extent and likely
cost of the damage is not yet known.
Initial reports said the incident happened as workers at the plant carried
out routine maintenance work on a distillation column used to purify
nitrotoluene.
Nitrotoluene is a flammable, toxic liquid produced as a feedstock for many
of Hickson's products, particularly pharmaceuticals, dyestuffs, pigments and
photographic products. Industrial grade toluene has a flash point of 2
degrees to 5 degrees centigrade.
One of the two maintenance workers was killed instantly in the explosion,
which destroyed the distillation column and set alight an adjoining
four-storey office block.
The other fatality and most of the injuries occurred in the office block.
Many more casualties could have been expected if the building had not been
almost empty during the lunchbreak.
Around 100 firefighters and 17 pumps attended the blaze, which was rapidly
extinguished, leaving a cloud of thick black smoke above the town. Residents
were advised to stay indoors and keep windows shut, but police later
confirmed that the smoke was not toxic.
Buildings near the plant were shaken by the blast.
Hickson International is Castleford's largest employer, providing around 800
jobs, and has been in the area for more than 50 years.
The company has recently undergone a series of board changes and been
reorganised after several poor acquisitions in the late 1980s. Pre-tax
profits more than doubled to Pounds 16.9m in the first half of this year.
Its shares fell 11p to 183p yesterday in late trading.
</TEXT>
