<DOCNO>FT923-1709</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIVBVAAPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920922
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 92 / Opt-out schools given cash pledge by Patten
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
JOHN PATTEN, education secretary, has promised that opt-out schools will
continue to get more cash than ordinary state schools.
The move followed fears of a slowing down in the pace of schools' becoming
grant-maintained under the government's flagship education policy because of
concerns about funding.
The 278 schools that have already opted out receive a significant budget
advantage once outside town hall control.
But this summer's white paper  - which provided a blueprint for all schools
to opt out into a new system without local education authorities  - was
unclear whether new grant-maintained schools would get the same preferential
treatment.
Critics say the clampdown on public spending made it unlikely, leaving heads
and governors wondering whether opting out was worth the risk.
Mr Patten has sought to maintain the momentum for opting out gained by the
Conservative election victory.
He told a party meeting in Aldershot on Friday: 'I intend to ensure that
schools which are accepted for grant-maintained status continue to receive
funding that recognises their extra responsibilities compared with LEA
schools.'
All opt-out schools would get a built-in advantage as part of the new common
funding formula proposed in the white paper, he said in the
little-publicised speech, which was not released until yesterday.
'It is important that parents and schools that are contemplating
grant-maintained status are aware of all these factors when coming to new
decisions,' he said.
Mr Patten said although the future of opt-out schools was 'totally secured',
there were question marks hanging over town halls as an independent
commission led by Sir John Banham, former director-general of the
Confederation of British Industry, investigated their future role, if any.
The government must start valuing teachers if its reforms are to improve
education, the Rev Dominic Milroy, chairman of the Headmasters' Conference
 -which represents 233 private schools  - said yesterday.
He said at the opening of the organisation's annual conference in Bruges:
'There appears to be a tendency in the public mind, and even for the
government, to lump teachers together as a profession which doesn't deserve
the same respect as the medical, legal or financial professions.'
Mr Milroy warned against the dangers of the 'exam league table mentality'
and performance pay for teachers.
</TEXT>
