<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 92 / Keen bidding for rare Meissen: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SUSAN MOORE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A COLLECTION of early and mid-18th-century Meissen porcelain found
exceptional prices at Christie's in London yesterday. The collection, by Dr
and Mrs Korthaus between the late 1940s and 1968, was of consistently high
quality and contained several rarities.
Keen bidding forced a top price of Pounds 77,000 (estimate Pounds
40,000-Pounds 50,000) for a chinoiserie table-bell and stand decorated with
harbour scenes, set in elaborate purl and gilt cartouches, and one of very
few examples to have survived intact. Other pieces from this apparently
unique tea and coffee service doubled their estimates.
A white ware beaker vase dating to the last days of the great Johann Bottger
also soared way over estimate, fetching Pounds 49,000. An oval armorial
sugar box and cover from the famous Swan Service, made by JJ Kandler and
Eberlein for the factory's director Count Bruhl, found a new owner at Pounds
48,400 (estimate Pounds 25,000-Pounds 35,000). The Korthaus collection
realised Pounds 613,910, with 19 of 68 lots unsold. A further 70 pieces will
be offered in the spring.
Outstanding istoriato or 'story-telling' majolica earthenware from the
collection of the late Sir Thomas Barlow fared less well. A dish of 1523-25
decorated by the Raphael of majolica painting, Nicola da Urbino, and a great
market rarity, was bought in at Pounds 60,000 (estimate Pounds 80,000-Pounds
120,000).
Another Urbino istoriato dish, by Francesco Xanto Avelli  - perhaps the most
extraordinary personality in the history of majolica  - was unsold at Pounds
26,000. Italian dealers and collectors, the prime supporters of the majolica
market, seemed to have stayed at home.
The sale of Continental ceramics totalled Pounds 775,148, with 70 per cent
sold by value.
</TEXT>
