FT  22 SEP 92 / Shorts' share in jet plan will secure jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Belfast Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PARTICIPATION in the development of a new business jet is expected to secure
between 700 and 800 jobs at Short Brothers, the Belfast aerospace company
now part of the Canadian Bombardier engineering group.
Learjet, the sister company of Shorts within Bombardier, yesterday announced
plans for the new medium-sized business aircraft, the Learjet 45, just
before the opening of the Dallas business aircraft show.
The Canadian company confirmed that the Belfast-based manufacturer will
design and build a significant proportion of the airframe.
Three Bombardier aerospace companies are participating in the project. Apart
from Learjet, de Havilland in Toronto will be responsible for the wings and
Shorts will design and manufacture the fuselage and build the tailplane in
Belfast.
Speaking from Dallas, Mr Roy McNulty, Shorts president, said he was
'delighted at this vote of confidence in Shorts' ability to play a major
part in the new Bombardier project'.
Preliminary design work has already started. Certification is scheduled for
1996.
The new aircraft will be able to carry eight to 10 passengers over a range
of 2,200 nautical miles at a cruise speed of Mach 0.81. Its 61-in cabin
width will be designed to provide greater comfort with more head and
shoulder room.
Shorts already employs more than 8,000 people in Northern Ireland and is the
province's largest private employer.
There was further good news on the economic front in Ulster yesterday with
an announcement by the Sandown group of private nursing homes that it is
creating 250 jobs through the provision of four new homes across the
province.
