<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 92 / MI5 'dirty tricks' report is denied
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND YARD last night denied reports that it believed MI5, the security
service, was behind a 'dirty tricks' campaign over the leak at the weekend
of the appointment of Commander David Tucker as the new head of Scotland
Yard's anti-terrorist branch.
The appointment was planned months ago as part of a reorganisation of the
security operations against IRA units active on the mainland, spearheaded by
Ms Stella Rimington, the MI5 chief, according to police sources.
It was not, Scotland Yard said, a way of hastening the retirement of
Commander George Churchill-Coleman. 'There is no MI5 dirty tricks behind
this,' it said.
The move came amid fears that any public escalation of a row between
Scotland Yard and MI5 might be exploited by the IRA.
However, anger at Scotland Yard continued to be widespread yesterday at the
way the leaking had in effect fore-stalled any chance of an uncontroversial
succession, due to take place in November.
According to one Scotland Yard official, the Home Office was under pressure
to identify those responsible for the leak, while Mr Churchill-Coleman was
said to be 'furious'.
</TEXT>
