<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 92 / UK Company News: Salvesen sells oil offshoot for Pounds
28.5m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHRISTIAN SALVESEN, the distribution, manufacturing and specialist hire
group, has sold its oilfield technology subsidiary for Pounds 28.5m to BJ
Services Company, of Houston, Texas.
The Aberdeen-based Salvesen (Oilfield Technology) had a net book value of
Pounds 15.8m and made operating profits of Pounds 3.3m in the year to March
31, which the group described as a difficult period in the North Sea oil
business.
Mr Chris Masters, Christian Salvesen's chief executive, said: 'The sale is
in line with our strategy of focusing on a limited number of activities
where we have a demonstrable and maintainable competitive edge.'
The proceeds will be used to reduce gearing, which stood at 35 per cent in
March. The consideration is being satisfied by a Pounds 15m 90-day loan note
and the balance in cash.
The disposal comes at a time when companies in the offshore supply business
face increasing competition for work as oil companies cut costs.
</TEXT>
