<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 92 / Pension fund theft insurance launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROVISION of unusual business at Lloyd's of London took a new turn
yesterday with an underwriter launching the first known insurance against
pension fund theft.
Syndicate 1007, managed by Spreckley Villers Hunt &amp; Co, is the lead
underwriter for insurance cover that will protect pension fund assets for up
to Pounds 50m.
The policy will provide 'first party' cover, which should permit prompt
reimbursement once theft has been established without the need for civil or
criminal action.
It defines theft as the dishonest appropriation of pension fund property
with the intention permanently to deprive the assured of that property.
It will apply to any theft by people or organisations that have control over
or access to pension fund assets. They include trustees and their employees,
administrators, investment managers, actuaries and directors.
Applicants will have to complete an eight-page form asking for details of
those involved in handling pension fund assets, how the fund manages and
handles investments and whether it takes part in stock lending.
Existing insurance cover has been available only for negligent errors or
omissions by pension fund trustees and not for deliberate fraud.
Mr Simon Haggas, an assistant underwriter, said the new idea was prompted by
the plight of the Maxwell pensioners. 'We were kicking ourselves about why
we had not done it before,' he said. 'It takes something like the Maxwell
affair to make it happen.'
Asked whether the introduction of the cover was a publicity stunt, he said:
'Oh, absolutely not. We are in it for the financial gain. We want to make
money out of the product.'
Losses caused by Hurricane Andrew in the Bahamas, Florida and Louisiana will
top Dollars 10bn, the Thomas Howell Group, loss adjusters, warned yesterday.
Estimates have been raised in Florida and delayed by slowness in claims
while residents concern themselves with food and shelter.
</TEXT>
