<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Ruutel falls short of Estonia target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TALLINN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ESTONIA'S first post-Soviet presidential elections appeared headed for an
inconclusive result early today as former communist leader Arnold Ruutel
failed to win an outright majority in most areas, Reuter reports from
Tallinn.
Mr Ruutel, chairman of parliament since 1983, had captured 43.1 per cent of
the total vote based on results from 17 out of 21 cities and counties,
including the capital Tallinn, election officials said.
His nearest rival, Mr Lennart Meri, a former foreign minister and leader of
the conservative Fatherland alliance, took 29.55 per cent.
The early results suggested Mr Ruutel would fall short of the 50 per cent
plus one vote needed to become the Baltic state's first freely elected
president since emerging from half a century of Soviet rule.
This means that the new president is likely to be chosen by parliament, also
elected yesterday.
Mr Meri's Fatherland alliance was widely expected to form the biggest party
in parliament, but results of that vote will not be known until today.
Russians, who make up about a third of the country's 1.6m population, were
barred from voting because under Estonian law they have no automatic right
to citizenship.
In the presidential vote, Mr Rein Taagepera, a Californian university
professor of Estonian birth, was close behind Mr Meri with 23.52 per cent,
while National Independence Party candidate Lagle Parek took 3.83 per cent.
</TEXT>
