<DOCNO>FT923-1797</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIUDDAEKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920921
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Leading Article: Indian reform can go on
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Manmohan Singh should be the toast of his peers at the International
Monetary Fund/World Bank annual meetings this week. In only 14 months, the
Indian finance minister has achieved what many would struggle to do in
years. With the strong backing of his prime minister, Mr P V Narasimha Rao,
he has overseen a change of direction in economic policy, and has persisted
with it.
The government took office when the country was in the depths of a payments
crisis and appeared in danger of being torn apart by internal dissent. That
dark time already seems long distant. Mr Rao and Mr Singh have put an
economy which had been isolated and strangled for decades by socialist
bureaucracy on course to openness and the free market, while remaining alert
to the needs of India's poor. Much more must be done. But if they manage to
maintain the momentum, they will create the base for a dynamic, open, and
huge economy in the second half of the 1990s.
This is all the more remarkable given that they are operating in one of the
world's most feverish democracies. China's reformers do not have to account
for themselves to voters, have so far taken 13 years to reform the economy,
and still have a long way to go.
Doubters, even within the government, have felt in recent months that the
early pace was slackening. Some have questioned the government's will,
others the pace at which it is feasible to push reform in India. The Bombay
stock market scandal forced the resignation of one of the leading reformers,
commerce minister Mr P Chidambaram, and occupied much of Mr Singh's time as
the scam became the subject of intense parliamentary argument. However, by
recent reductions in fertiliser and petroleum subsidies, Mr Singh has
demonstrated that he remains determined.
Though not by nature a politician, Mr Singh is commendably frank in
admitting the political difficulties he faces in taking the next steps of
reform. But visible progress must continue to be made if growth in
international confidence is to continue. Foreign companies, other than those
who had been working for years to get investments through and suddenly found
the dam broken, have so far not backed their support with very much hard
cash. Without substantial private inflows, the reform programme will falter.
Potential investors want to see progress on several fronts. Employers need
to know on what basis they can hire and fire. A clear 'exit policy' has yet
to be enunciated. Mr Singh has, perhaps sensibly, tackled one industry first
and won agreement with labour unions on reorganising textile factories. This
alone will involve the loss of 70,000 jobs. He has to tread carefully when
new job opportunities are scarce and the safety net precarious or
non-existent.
On reducing the size of the public sector, Mr Singh feels that he does not
have a popular mandate for full-scale privatisation. Measures taken so far
have been tentative and insufficient. Big state-owned industries and banks
mostly need new management and new capital. New ownership is the best way to
achieve this given the bureaucracy with which they mostly remain encumbered.
Agriculture urgently needs new investment to restore its growth to
respectable levels. The tax structure must be reformed to broaden the tax
net, reduce reliance on customs duties and therefore allow further
reductions in import tariffs which will help to force Indian industry to
become more competitive.
Mr Singh will be heartened by recent signs that the economy is responding to
fiscal and monetary tightness. This will help him win support for continued
reform. Exports to convertible currency areas are showing faster though not
spectacular growth. A convincing upturn in industrial production is still
awaited. But year-on-year inflation is running just below the 8 per cent
target for the financial year, and the fiscal deficit has been sharply
reduced. The stability of the rupee since it was made partially convertible
this year may well encourage Mr Singh to go for full convertibility within a
few months.
His approach in all these areas must be steadfast, though not so bold that
the whole game is lost. The international community is aware of the
political battles he faces. But he has already shown just how much can be
achieved, against the political odds, by determined good government. He must
press on, and he must be allowed to do so.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
